Much light has, however, been thrown on this subject by the labours ofmodern scholars, especially Ritschl, and one leading principle has been established with tolerable certainty: viz. that the scansion depends on the accent ol the word as spoken, and not on any rigid rlrles of Prosody, such as were observed by the Augustan poets.
